President Barack Obama has announced his intent to nominate Jeffrey DeLaurentis as the first U.S. Ambassador to Cuba in over 50 years. DeLaurentis is currently serving as Chief of Mission at the U.S. Embassy in Havana and has extensive experience in Cuba and Latin America. He has been instrumental in the normalization of relations between the United States and Cuba and has worked on various issues such as law enforcement, counternarcotics, environmental protection, and cooperation in science and health. If confirmed by the Senate, DeLaurentis will continue to support the Cuban people and advance America's interests in Cuba. He has previously served as Ambassador and Alternate Representative for Special Political Affairs at the U.S. Mission to the United Nations, Deputy Assistant Secretary of State for the Bureau of Western Hemisphere Affairs, and in other overseas posts. DeLaurentis holds a B.S. from Georgetown University School of Foreign Service and an M.A. from Columbia University's School of International and Public Affairs.